         <abstract>
            <p>Given a weight function ω(x) on (α, β), and a system of polynomials {p&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;(x)}&lt;sup&gt;∞&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;k = 0&lt;/sub&gt;, with degree p&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;(x) = k, we consider the problem of constructing Gaussian quadrature rules &lt;tex-math&gt;$\int^\beta_\alpha f(x)\omega(x)dx \doteq = \sum^n_{r = 1} \lambda^{(n)}_r f(\xi^{(n)}_r}$&lt;/tex-math&gt; from "modified moments" ν&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt; = ∫&lt;sup&gt;β&lt;/sup&gt;&lt;sub&gt;α&lt;/sub&gt; p&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;(x)ω(x)dx. Classical procedures take p&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;(x) = x&lt;sup&gt;k&lt;/sup&gt;, but suffer from progressive ill-conditioning as n increases. A more recent procedure, due to Sack and Donovan, takes for {p&lt;sub&gt;k&lt;/sub&gt;(x)} a system of (classical) orthogonal polynomials. The problem is then remarkably well-conditioned, at least for finite intervals [ α, β ]. In support of this observation, we obtain upper bounds for the respective asymptotic condition number. In special cases, these bounds grow like a fixed power of n. We also derive an algorithm for solving the problem considered, which generalizes one due to Golub and Welsch. Finally, some numerical examples are presented.</p>
          </abstract>
